[3] USA (Nebraska, Omaha) alert
Date: Thu 23 Mar 2017 5:43 PM
Source: KETV [edited]
http://www.ketv.com/article/measles-case-exposures-in-douglas-sarpy-counties/9173888


Nebraska and county health experts say a person with the measles exposed others to the disease in Douglas and Sarpy counties over a three-day period in mid-March [2017].

According to an alert by the Nebraska Department of Health and Human Services, the measles case involved a passenger aboard a Delta Airlines flight from Minneapolis to Omaha on [Sun 12 Mar 2017].

The alert says all of those exposed to the person have been notified. The exposures took place in locations [that can be found in the full report at the URL above].

"If people visited one of the locations and comes down with a fever and a rash, they should see a health care provider," said Dr Tom Safranek, State Epidemiologist for the Nebraska Department of Health and Human Services.

Health care providers are advised to report any rash or fever illnesses with exposures to the Nebraska Department of Health and Human Services.

Incubation period time from exposure to onset of symptoms is usually around 14 days.

Measles starts with fever, sore throat, cough, runny nose and red eyes. A full-body rash follows those symptoms, which can take 2 weeks to develop. Measles is highly contagious and spreads through sneezing and coughing. The CDC urges you to make sure you and your children get the measles, mumps and rubella vaccine.

